The alternative release scenario is one more likely to occur than the worst-case scenario, unless no release occurs. In this scenario, 25,000 gallons of aqueous ammonia is released from the storage tank into the diked enclosure.  No controls were assumed, even though row valves may be utilized in an emergency to mitigate releases. Also, less than 25,000 gallons of aqueous ammonia will be typically present. Under neutral weather conditions (stability Class D) and wind speed of 3 meters/second, the maximum distance to the toxic endpoint of 0.14 mg/L is<0.10 miles. 



We determined that there are no public receptors within the worst-case or alternative release scenarios.  There have been no accidents at the Greater Des Moines Energy Center.  Therefore, this process qualifies for Program Level 1. The Greater Des Moines Energy Center's responsibility under Program Level 1 is as follows:



* Submit a single RMP, as provided in A?68.150 to 68.185. The RMP shall include a registration that reflects all covered processes.

* Analyze the worst-case release scenario for the process, as provided in A?68.25; document that the nearest public receptor is beyond the distance to a toxic or flammable endpoint defined in A?68.22(a); and submit in the RMP the worst-case release scenario as provided in A?68.165;

* Complete the five-year accident history for the process as provided in A?68.42 of this part and submit it in the RMP as provided in A?68.168;

* For Program 1 processes, the owner or operator shall submit in the RMP the certification statement provided in A?68.12(b)(4); 

